lead_paragraph: Julius Shulman, the legendary photographer who helped make California Modernist architecture famous around the world, died on July 15 at the age of 98. Shulman produced images of buildings -- by pioneering architects like Richard Neutra, John Lautner and Pierre Koenig - that defined the postwar architecture of Southern California, among other places. The gregarious and seemingly tireless photographer continued to work until shortly before his death; in a 2007 interview in T Design, Shulman sang the praises of Arne Jacobsen's classic Egg chair; the renowned architect sent him two as a thank-you gift after a photo shoot in the 1950s.

lead_paragraph: The folks at Vulture point us to this CTV obituary for the Canadian actor Les Lye, who died on Tuesday at the age of 84. Mr. Lye, a veteran broadcaster and performer, might have gone unnoticed in the United States were it not for his time as a cast member on the kiddie comedy show “You Can’t Do That on Television.” On that show, a sort of junior version of “Laugh-In” that had its premiere in 1979 on the Ottawa station CJOH-TV, Mr. Lye appeared in comedy sketches with the show’s young performers, playing foils like Barth (of the greasy hamburger stand Barth’s Burgery) and the captain of a firing squad (that was usually about to execute the children). When “You Can’t Do That on Television” was shown on Nickelodeon in the early 1980s, it quickly became one of that channel’s most popular programs.

lead_paragraph: SUCHER--Laurie, died peacefully at home in Chicago on May 26, 2009 surrounded by love and music. She is survived by her husband, Michael Gaster, their sons, Toby, Jonah and Gabriel Gaster, her brother, David Sucher, cousins Diana and Roger Glassman. She touched many lives, leaving close friends who loved her dearly. A native NYer, she graduated from the H.S. of Music and Art, Barnard, and SUNY Stony Brook, where she received a Ph.D in English and published a well received study of Ruth Prawer Jhabvala. (She later taught at Truman College in Chicago, where she lived for 30 years. Also a gifted musician and artist, she was a cantorial soloist leading high holiday services, sang and performed classical, popular, Yiddish, Ladino, and Renaissance music, and exhibited her paintings in many galleries. For her wonderful tireless spirit, her sense of humor and adventure, her relentless spiritual quest, her original and quirky intelligence and her loyalty to us all, she is already more than missed. lead_paragraph: I read in The Times this morning, to my surprise, that Peter L. Bernstein had died. True, he was 90 years old, but he had been active, engaged -- and working -- until a few days ago, when he broke his hip and then died of pneumonia in the hospital. Mr. Bernstein was perhaps best known for two books he wrote at a stage in life when most people are retired: "Against The Gods: The Remarkable Story of Risk," and "Capital Ideas: The Improbable Origins of Modern Wall Street." As my colleague Louis Uchitelle noted in his affectionate obituary, Mr. Bernstein was a firm believer in the efficient market theory -- the subject of my column last Saturday -- and especially the power of diversification, which he touted constantly. He founded The Journal of Portfolio Theory. Harry Markowitz, who was awarded a Nobel Prize, for, essentially, creating portfolio theory, was one of his heroes. Mr. Bernstein's last book, "Capital Ideas Evolving," published two years ago, was an attempt (more successful than not) at incorporating some of the ideas of behavioral finance into the broader efficient market theory championed by the likes of Mr. Markowitz and Eugene Fama of the University of Chicago.
